EMPLOYEE RETENTION PREDICITVE ANALYSIS

DEFINE PROBLEM

Background: Frequent voluntary turnover has a negative impact on employee morale, productivity, and company revenue. Recruiting and training a new employee requires staff time and money. According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, turnover is highest in industries such as trade and utilities, construction, retail, customer service, hospitality, and service.

Objective: The purpose of this project is to build several models that predict employee retention/turnover of employees. The sample data is from employees previous exit interviews. The data set contains variables such as employee satisfaction, number of projects, salary level,last evaluation, average monthly hours, position, time at the company, promotion during last five years, and work accidents.

DATA TRANFORMATIONS

As mentioned earlier, two of the variables (sales[job position] and salary) are factors. Salary in particular could quite possibly play a role in time spent with company. I am created dummy variables so the numeric representation can be used in the models.

hrdata2 <- cbind (hrdata, dummy(hrdata$Department), dummy(hrdata$salary))

I am splitting the data set (hrdata2) into training and testing data. Used the createDataPartition function from the caret package.

set.seed(102)
trainData <- createDataPartition(y = hrdata2$time_spend_company, 
                               p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train <- hrdata2[trainData,]
test <- hrdata2[-trainData,]

DATA MODELING

Set up resampling and 10-fold cross validation.

set.seed(100)
tr <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, repeats = 5)
